    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i looked at the pool size and it's already at 50. i also checked the queries and they seem pretty optimized, nothing is hanging for a long time. it's just weird because it's so intermittent. like, most of the time it works fine, then suddenly it just dies under load. it feels almost random, like there's something hidden causing it to spike. any other architectural things i should look at?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic \"hidden bottleneck\" scenario, often caused by something that isn't immediately visible in the standard query logs, much like a sneaky goblin hiding in the shadows of your server room. Even with 50 connections and optimized queries, there are a few architectural culprits that can cause this intermittent explosion, and I suspect one of them is lurking right next to your database.\n\nFirst, consider **connection leaks**. Even if your queries are fast, if a single request holds onto a connection for a split second longer than expected (maybe a background task or a slow external API call), it eats up your precious pool. Imagine a line of people at a checkout counter; if one person forgets to leave the counter and starts chatting with the cashier, the next person waits forever, even though the line is moving fine for everyone else. This is often invisible until the pool is completely full.\n\nSecond, look at **external dependencies**. Are you hitting any third-party services (like payment gateways, email providers, or analytics tools) during the `finalize_transaction` step? If one of those services is slow or flaky, it can block your entire transaction, effectively freezing your connection. It's like a construction crew building",
      "source": "target",
